{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_01RhbRxYU1J7tgtWJ5NParZA","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"tool_use","id":"toolu_013mJsCndsMcUVq1t2ZaYWHB","name":"Bash","input":{"command":"kubectl -n elasticsearch create configmap config-audit --from-literal=findings.txt=\"$(cat <<'FINDINGS_EOF'\nELASTICSEARCH SECURITY & OPERATIONAL COMPLIANCE AUDIT\nCluster: es-cluster  |  Version: 8.11.1  |  Nodes: 3  |  Date: 2026-06-25\nAuditor: automated read-only audit (no cluster changes made)\n================================================================================\n\nEXECUTIVE SUMMARY\n-----------------\nThe cluster has a baseline security posture (TLS enabled, authentication\nenforced, non-root pods). However, several high-severity gaps exist that deviate\nfrom Elasticsearch hardening baselines and Kubernetes security best practices.\nRemediation should be prioritised in severity order below.\n\n\nSEVERITY LEGEND:  [CRITICAL] [HIGH] [MEDIUM] [LOW] [INFO] [PASS]\n\n\n=== SECTION 1: AUTHENTICATION & AUTHORIZATION ===\n\n[PASS] xpack.security.enabled = true  — Security X-Pack is active.\n\n[PASS] Anonymous access blocked  — unauthenticated requests return HTTP 401.\n\n[PASS] Password hashing algorithm: BCRYPT  — industry-standard adaptive hash.\n\n[PASS] No active API keys  — _security/api_key returns empty set.\n\n[PASS] No custom roles defined  — only built-in reserved roles are present;\n       no over-privileged custom roles exist.\n\n[PASS] action.destructive_requires_name = true  — wildcard index deletion\n       (DELETE /*) is blocked.\n\n[MEDIUM] DEPRECATED USER \"kibana\" STILL ENABLED\n       The legacy `kibana` user (role: kibana_system) is enabled despite being\n       deprecated since ES 8.x. Elastic recommends using `kibana_system` user\n       exclusively. An enabled legacy account broadens the credential attack\n       surface unnecessarily.\n       Evidence: GET /_security/user/kibana -> enabled: true, deprecated: true\n\n[MEDIUM] ELASTIC SUPERUSER PASSWORD IS WEAK / PREDICTABLE\n       The `elastic` superuser password stored in secret elastic-password is a\n       low-entropy, predictable string (\"elasticpass-elastic-password-next\").\n       It contains no uppercase letters or special characters, follows a\n       recognisable naming pattern, and appears to be a placeholder value.\n       This is the most privileged account; any compromise grants full cluster\n       control.\n\n[MEDIUM] STALLED PASSWORD ROTATION SUSPECTED\n       Two secrets exist: elastic-password and elastic-password-next.\n       Both secrets currently contain the SAME password value. This indicates\n       a rotation was initiated but not completed, leaving the cluster in an\n       ambiguous credential state. The \"next\" password provides no security\n       benefit if it is identical to the current one.\n\n[LOW] run_as PRIVILEGE ENABLED CLUSTER-WIDE\n       xpack.security.authc.run_as.enabled = true (default). This allows\n       any user granted the run_as privilege to impersonate other users.\n       Review all roles to ensure no unintended run_as grants exist.\n\n[INFO] xpack.security.authc.token.enabled = false  — short-lived bearer tokens\n       are disabled; only Basic and API-key auth methods are active.\n\n\n=== SECTION 2: TLS / ENCRYPTION IN TRANSIT ===\n\n[PASS] HTTP SSL enabled: xpack.security.http.ssl.enabled = true\n[PASS] Transport SSL enabled: xpack.security.transport.ssl.enabled = true\n[PASS] Negotiated protocol: TLSv1.3 (Cipher: TLS_AES_256_GCM_SHA384)  — \n       strongest available TLS version confirmed via openssl handshake.\n[PASS] Ingress force-ssl-redirect = true  — HTTP->HTTPS redirect enforced.\n\n[HIGH] TRANSPORT SSL VERIFICATION MODE: \"certificate\" (NOT \"full\")\n       elasticsearch.yml sets:\n         xpack.security.transport.ssl.verification_mode: certificate\n       This validates the certificate chain but does NOT verify the hostname.\n       An attacker with a cert signed by the same CA can perform a man-in-the-\n       middle attack on inter-node transport (port 9300) traffic. The baseline\n       hardening recommendation is verification_mode: full.\n\n[HIGH] INGRESS BACKEND TLS VERIFICATION DISABLED\n       The NGINX ingress is configured with:\n         nginx.ingress.kubernetes.io/proxy-ssl-verify: \"off\"\n       This means traffic from the ingress controller to the ES HTTP service\n       is encrypted but the ES backend certificate is NOT verified. A rogue\n       endpoint or pod could intercept that segment without detection.\n       Recommendation: set proxy-ssl-verify: \"on\" and supply the CA cert.\n\n[MEDIUM] SELF-SIGNED CA — NOT TRUSTED BY STANDARD CLIENTS\n       HTTP cert:    Subject CN=es-http,   Issuer CN=es-ca     (self-signed CA)\n       Ingress cert: Subject CN=es.example.com, Issuer CN=es.example.com\n                     (self-signed, CA is the cert itself)\n       Neither CA is a publicly trusted root. External or new internal clients\n       must explicitly trust these CAs. Risk: certificate pinning bypass, MITM\n       if the CA private key is not strictly protected.\n       CA key is stored in Kubernetes secret es-http-tls (accessible to any\n       pod with secret read permissions in the namespace).\n\n[INFO] HTTP TLS certificates:\n       Not Before: 2026-06-25 01:40:21 UTC\n       Not After:  2027-06-25 01:40:21 UTC  (365 days)\n       SANs: localhost, *.elasticsearch.svc, *.elasticsearch.svc.cluster.local\n       Note: SANs cover cluster-internal FQDNs but NOT external hostnames;\n       external clients connecting via Ingress receive the ingress cert, not\n       this internal cert.\n\n[INFO] Ingress TLS certificate:\n       Not Before: 2026-06-25 02:14:57 UTC\n       Not After:  2026-06-25 02:14:57 UTC (365 days)\n       SAN: DNS:es.example.com only.\n\n\n=== SECTION 3: AUDIT LOGGING ===\n\n[CRITICAL] AUDIT LOGGING IS DISABLED\n       xpack.security.audit.enabled = false\n       No audit trail is produced for authentication events, access grants,\n       access denials, configuration changes, or privileged operations.\n       This is a primary compliance control required by SOC2, PCI-DSS, HIPAA,\n       ISO 27001, and most security baselines. Without audit logs:\n         - Breaches cannot be detected or investigated.\n         - Unauthorized access leaves no forensic trace.\n         - Compliance attestations are unsupportable.\n       The default event filters include ACCESS_DENIED, AUTHENTICATION_FAILED,\n       and SECURITY_CONFIG_CHANGE — enabling the flag with default filters\n       would immediately provide meaningful coverage.\n\n\n=== SECTION 4: NETWORK EXPOSURE & POLICIES ===\n\n[MEDIUM] NO KUBERNETES NETWORK POLICIES DEFINED\n       kubectl get networkpolicy -n elasticsearch returns: No resources found.\n       Every pod in the cluster (across all namespaces, depending on CNI\n       configuration) can reach Elasticsearch on port 9200 and 9300. Lateral\n       movement from a compromised pod anywhere in the cluster directly\n       exposes the ES API and inter-node transport.\n       Recommendation: define ingress NetworkPolicies restricting port 9200\n       to known consumer namespaces and port 9300 to the ES StatefulSet pods\n       only.\n\n[LOW] ALL NODES BIND TO ALL INTERFACES (network.host: 0.0.0.0)\n       Combined with no NetworkPolicies, every node interface is reachable.\n       Standard for Kubernetes pods, but noted as an amplifier for the\n       missing-network-policy finding above.\n\n[INFO] Elasticsearch is exposed externally via Ingress:\n       Name: elasticsearch-ingress (namespace: elasticsearch)\n       Host: es.example.com  |  Class: nginx\n       Backend: es-http:9200 (HTTPS)\n       The ingress terminates external TLS (es-ingress-tls secret) and\n       re-encrypts to the backend (proxy-ssl-verify: off — see Section 2).\n       Port 80 traffic is force-redirected to 443.\n\n\n=== SECTION 5: CLUSTER SETTINGS ===\n\n[MEDIUM] MEMORY LOCK DISABLED (bootstrap.memory_lock: false)\n       Elasticsearch heap and index data can be swapped to disk. This degrades\n       performance and, on unencrypted volumes, risks persisting sensitive\n       indexed data in swap. For production deployments, memory locking should\n       be enabled (requires ulimit -l unlimited on the host).\n\n[MEDIUM] WATCHER SENSITIVE DATA ENCRYPTION DISABLED\n       xpack.watcher.encrypt_sensitive_data = false\n       Watcher action configurations (e.g., email credentials, webhook tokens)\n       are stored in plaintext in the cluster state. If cluster state is\n       exported or snapshotted, credentials in Watcher configs are exposed.\n\n[LOW] AUTO INDEX CREATION ENABLED (action.auto_create_index: true)\n       Any authenticated user with index write privileges can implicitly create\n       new indices. This can lead to index sprawl and unintentional data\n       landing outside governed index templates. Recommend restricting to\n       known index patterns or disabling unless required.\n\n[LOW] FIPS 140-2 MODE DISABLED (xpack.security.fips_mode.enabled: false)\n       Required for regulated environments (FedRAMP, government, certain\n       financial sector mandates). Note: enabling FIPS mode requires FIPS-\n       capable JVM and certificate format changes; plan accordingly.\n\n[LOW] HTTP RESPONSE COMPRESSION DISABLED (http.compression: false)\n       HTTP response bodies are not compressed. While disabling compression\n       is a mitigation against BREACH-style attacks (and therefore may be\n       intentional), it increases bandwidth for high-throughput workloads.\n       Document the intent if this is a deliberate security setting.\n\n[PASS] action.destructive_requires_name = true  — noted also in Section 1.\n\n[INFO] Cluster health: GREEN  (3/3 nodes active, 0 unassigned shards)\n[INFO] Active shards: 0  (no user indices present)\n[INFO] Max shards per node: 1000 (default)\n\n\n=== SECTION 6: NODE ROLES & TOPOLOGY ===\n\n[LOW] NO ROLE SEPARATION — ALL NODES ARE master+data+ingest\n       All 3 nodes carry roles: master, data, ingest.\n       This is acceptable for small clusters but means master elections compete\n       with data-intensive workloads. A split-brain or OOM event on a data-\n       heavy node can destabilise cluster leadership. For production, dedicated\n       master-eligible nodes (no data/ingest roles) are recommended for\n       clusters expecting significant load.\n       Current node roles:\n         elasticsearch-0: [master, data, ingest]\n         elasticsearch-1: [master, data, ingest]\n         elasticsearch-2: [master, data, ingest]\n\n[INFO] All 3 nodes healthy, transport reachable on port 9300.\n[INFO] JVM heap: -Xms512m / -Xmx512m per node (resource limits: 2Gi RAM, 2 CPU)\n\n\n=== SECTION 7: KUBERNETES / POD SECURITY ===\n\n[PASS] Pods run as non-root: runAsNonRoot=true, runAsUser=1000, fsGroup=1000\n[PASS] Resource limits set: CPU 2 cores, Memory 2Gi per pod.\n[PASS] Readiness and startup probes configured.\n\n[LOW] DEFAULT SERVICE ACCOUNT IN USE\n       Pods use the `default` service account with no custom RBAC. If the\n       workload node/pod is compromised, the service account token grants\n       whatever the default SA is bound to. In environments with broad\n       cluster-level roles, this can be significant. Audit default SA\n       permissions for the elasticsearch namespace.\n\n[LOW] CA PRIVATE KEY ACCESSIBLE AS A SECRET\n       The es-http-tls secret contains the CA private key (ca.crt, tls.crt,\n       tls.key). Any pod or service account with read access to secrets in\n       the elasticsearch namespace can extract the CA key and issue valid\n       certificates trusted by the cluster. Store CA private keys in an\n       external secret manager or Vault rather than in cluster secrets.\n\n[INFO] No container securityContext-level settings observed\n       (readOnlyRootFilesystem, allowPrivilegeEscalation, seccompProfile).\n       Consider adding these to reduce pod attack surface.\n\n\n=== SECTION 8: BACKUP & OPERATIONAL CONTINUITY ===\n\n[HIGH] NO SNAPSHOT REPOSITORY CONFIGURED\n       GET /_snapshot returns {}.\n       There is no backup mechanism in place. A cluster failure, data\n       corruption, or accidental destructive operation (e.g., index deletion)\n       would result in permanent data loss. A backup strategy (S3, GCS, Azure,\n       or shared filesystem snapshot repo) should be configured and tested\n       before the cluster holds any production data.\n\n[INFO] ILM policies: only built-in Elastic system policies exist.\n       No user-defined ILM policies are configured.\n       No data streams or user indices exist at time of audit.\n\n\n=== SECTION 9: USERS & ROLES INVENTORY ===\n\nBuilt-in users (all enabled unless noted):\n  elastic          — roles: [superuser]              ENABLED\n  kibana_system    — roles: [kibana_system]           ENABLED\n  kibana           — roles: [kibana_system]           ENABLED (DEPRECATED)\n  logstash_system  — roles: [logstash_system]         ENABLED\n  beats_system     — roles: [beats_system]            ENABLED\n  apm_system       — roles: [apm_system]              ENABLED\n  remote_monitoring_user — roles: [remote_monitoring_collector,\n                                    remote_monitoring_agent] ENABLED\n\nNo custom users or roles defined.\nNo role mappings configured (external auth integration not in use).\n\n\n=== PRIORITISED REMEDIATION CHECKLIST ===\n\nPriority 1 — CRITICAL (fix immediately):\n  [ ] Enable audit logging: xpack.security.audit.enabled = true\n      Add to elasticsearch.yml and rolling-restart the cluster.\n\nPriority 2 — HIGH (fix before production load):\n  [ ] Change transport SSL verification: verification_mode: full\n  [ ] Enable ingress backend cert verification: proxy-ssl-verify: \"on\"\n      (supply es-http-tls CA cert to ingress via proxy-ssl-secret annotation)\n  [ ] Configure at least one snapshot repository and test restore.\n\nPriority 3 — MEDIUM (fix in next sprint):\n  [ ] Rotate elastic superuser password to a high-entropy random value.\n      Complete or abandon the stalled rotation (elastic-password-next secret).\n  [ ] Disable deprecated `kibana` user.\n  [ ] Define and apply Kubernetes NetworkPolicies for the namespace.\n  [ ] Enable memory locking: bootstrap.memory_lock = true\n      (requires matching ulimit in pod spec / init container).\n  [ ] Enable Watcher data encryption: xpack.watcher.encrypt_sensitive_data = true\n\nPriority 4 — LOW (planned hardening):\n  [ ] Separate node roles: dedicate 3 master-only nodes + data nodes for scale.\n  [ ] Restrict auto index creation: set action.auto_create_index to known patterns.\n  [ ] Add pod-level security settings: readOnlyRootFilesystem, seccompProfile.\n  [ ] Move CA private key to external secret manager.\n  [ ] Create a dedicated service account with minimal RBAC for ES pods.\n\n\nEND OF AUDIT REPORT\nFINDINGS_EOF\n)\" 2>&1","description":"Create config-audit ConfigMap with comprehensive security findings"},"caller":{"type":"direct"}}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":580,"cache_read_input_tokens":55649,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":580},"output_tokens":29,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"diagnostics":null,"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"06a4ab4b-50d6-46d2-b54a-a3980899b9e8","uuid":"4e507d9d-344e-4787-b9e9-624878cd6120","request_id":"req_011CcPB9E8i1ZwsoBg4gNpwT"}
